		<description>Yes, I know, although I didn&#039;t mention it. I guess bias comes from my background, which is software development.

I haven&#039;t yet seen a patent, which is both non-obvious and revealing.  It seems wast majority is either one or the other.

But the question is still, is making these ideas public worth 28 years of monopoly? Would we really have to wait at least that long before we could reproduce it ourselves otherwise?

I&#039;d say no, judging by the speed at which software industry developed before software patents even existed.</description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Yes, I know, although I didn&#8217;t mention it. I guess bias comes from my background, which is software development.</p>
<p>I haven&#8217;t yet seen a patent, which is both non-obvious and revealing.  It seems wast majority is either one or the other.</p>
<p>But the question is still, is making these ideas public worth 28 years of monopoly? Would we really have to wait at least that long before we could reproduce it ourselves otherwise?</p>
<p>I&#8217;d say no, judging by the speed at which software industry developed before software patents even existed.</p>
